.TH MAIL9P 4
.SH NAME
mail9p \- IMAP/SMTP mailbox as a 9P filesystem
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mail9p
[
.B -D
] [
.B -m
.I mountpoint
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Mail9p
exposes one or more IMAP4rev1 mailboxes (RFC 3501) as a Plan 9-style
filesystem so an agent can read, classify, flag, move, and (separately)
reply to mail using ordinary file operations. Credentials live in
.IR factotum (4);
.I mail9p
never sees them on its own command line.
.PP
By default it mounts at
.BR /n/mail .
The
.B -m
flag relocates the mount; the
.B -D
flag enables Styx tracing on stderr.
.SH FILESYSTEM
.TF accounts/
.TP
.B ctl
write-only:
.BR "connect " "\fIname server\fP [\fBtls\fP|\fBstarttls\fP] [\fBoauth\fP] [\fBsmtp=\fP\fIhost\fP]"
opens an IMAP session and best-effort SELECTs INBOX. The
.B oauth
flag selects SASL XOAUTH2 (OAuth2 bearer token) instead of password
LOGIN \(em required for providers such as Gmail that no longer accept
passwords;
.BR "disconnect " \fIname\fP
LOGOUTs and frees the slot;
.BR "sync " \fIname\fP
re-fetches the folder list and re-SELECTs the current mailbox.
.TP
.B accounts/
one entry per connected account.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /ctl
read: status line
.RB ( connected | disconnected ", " "box=" "\fIname\fP, " "exists=" "N, " "unseen=" "N" );
write:
.BR "select " \fImailbox\fP
or
.BR sync .
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /compose
write-only. Writes a full RFC822 message; it is sent via SMTP using
factotum credentials. Recipients are extracted from the
.B To:
header unless overridden.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/
one entry per server-reported mailbox.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box /ctl
write:
.BR "search " \fIimap-criteria\fP
runs IMAP SEARCH; the matching UIDs land in the same ctl file (one
per line) and are returned on the next
.B read.
.BR "archive " \fIuid\fP
COPYs the message to
.B Archive
and STOREs
.BR \eDeleted .
.BR "move " "\fIuid\fP \fIdest-box\fP"
COPYs then STOREs
.BR \eDeleted .
Operations only succeed against the currently-selected box; SELECT
via the account ctl first.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid
one directory per message in the currently-selected box, named by
IMAP UID. Non-current boxes are listable but have no message
sub-entries (select the box first).
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /from
.PD 0
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /to
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /cc
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /subject
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /date
.PD
read-only header fields, parsed from the IMAP envelope.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /flags
read: space-separated flag tokens (\fB\eSeen\fP, \fB\eFlagged\fP, ...).
.br
write: replace mode (\fB\eSeen \eFlagged\fP) sets the exact flag set;
diff mode (\fB+\eSeen -\eFlagged\fP) adds or removes individual
flags. Mixing the two styles in a single write is an error.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /body
text section of the message (everything after the first blank line).
Fetched lazily and cached.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /body.html
empty in v1. MIME parsing is out of scope; consumers that need
HTML should parse
.B raw
themselves.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /raw
full RFC822 message (headers + body). Fetched lazily and cached.
.TP
.BI accounts/ name /boxes/ box / uid /draft-reply
write-only. The body is sent via SMTP with
.BR Subject ,
.BR To ,
.BR In-Reply-To ,
and
.B References
auto-injected from the original envelope (the caller's body wins if
it already supplies any of them). On success the original message is
STOREd
.BR \eAnswered .
.SH CAPABILITY MODEL
The namespace is the only enforcement primitive. Bind paths into a
sub-agent's namespace to grant capabilities; refuse to bind to deny
them:
.PP
.RS
.PD 0
.TP
\fBTriage-only\fP:
bind
.B from to subject date flags
and
.BR boxes/.../ctl ;
do not bind
.BR compose
or
.BR draft-reply .
.TP
\fBReply-allowed\fP:
additionally bind specific
.B draft-reply
files per thread.
.TP
\fBCompose-from-scratch\fP:
additionally bind
.BR compose .
.PD
.RE
.PP
There is no permission system inside
.IR mail9p .
.SH AUTHENTICATION
IMAP credentials are read from
.IR factotum (4)
at connect time using
.PP
.B proto=pass service=imap dom=\fIserver\fP
.PP
SMTP send tries the
.BR service=smtp
key first and falls back to the
.BR service=imap
key for the corresponding IMAP server, since most providers share
credentials. SMTP transport mirrors the account's IMAP mode:
implicit TLS over port 465 when IMAPS is in use, plaintext port 25
otherwise. STARTTLS on SMTP is not yet supported.
.PP
For an
.B oauth
account, credentials are held in a single
.IR factotum (4)
key:
.PP
.EX
proto=pass service=imap-oauth dom=\fIserver\fP user=\fIemail\fP \e
    client_id=\fIid\fP client_secret=\fIsecret\fP \e
    token_uri=\fIurl\fP !password=\fIrefresh-token\fP
.EE
.PP
The refresh token is the key's
.B !password
(retrieved via
.IR factotum 's
getuserpasswd); the public
.BR client_id ", " client_secret " and " token_uri
attributes are read from
.BR /mnt/factotum/ctl .
At connect time and before each send,
.I mail9p
POSTs the refresh grant to
.B token_uri
.RB ( token_uri
defaults to Google's endpoint if absent) and authenticates IMAP and
SMTP with the resulting short-lived access token. The OAuth client and
refresh token are obtained out of band; the OAuth authorisation flow
itself is not implemented here.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Connect, list folders, read the latest message in INBOX, mark it
read:
.IP
.EX
mail9p
echo connect work imap.fastmail.com > /n/mail/ctl
ls /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes
last=`{ls /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX | grep -v ctl | tail -1}
cat /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/$last/subject
cat /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/$last/body
echo '\eSeen' > /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/$last/flags
.EE
.PP
Search and archive:
.IP
.EX
echo 'search FROM noreply@example.com' > /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/ctl
for u in `{cat /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/ctl} {
    echo 'archive '^$u > /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/ctl
}
.EE
.PP
Reply with threading headers auto-injected:
.IP
.EX
echo 'Got it, thanks.' > /n/mail/accounts/work/boxes/INBOX/$last/draft-reply
.EE
.SH FILES
.TF /dis/mail9p.dis
.TP
.B /dis/mail9p.dis
binary
.TP
.B /dis/lib/mailparse.dis
shared parser library (also used by the test suite)
.TP
.B /mnt/factotum
credential source
.SH SOURCE
.B /appl/cmd/mail9p.b
.PP
.B /appl/lib/mailparse.b
.SH BUGS
MIME parsing is not implemented; the
.B body.html
file is always empty. Use
.B raw
and parse it yourself.
.PP
Only the currently-selected mailbox surfaces message contents under
.BR boxes/<box>/<uid>/ .
Non-selected boxes are visible as directories but have no message
entries until SELECTed via the account ctl.
.PP
Archive and move STORE
.B \eDeleted
but do not EXPUNGE, mirroring Gmail-style retention. There is no
EXPUNGE verb exposed yet.
.PP
STARTTLS for SMTP is not supported; sends go over plain port 25 or
implicit TLS port 465.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR factotum (4),
.IR llmsrv (4),
.IR styx (5)
